  "text": "Subsequently, the electrochemical properties of 2 were studied. The bulk-modified carbon paste electrode (CPE) does not dissolve in water and common organic solvents, so we chose it. The 2-modified CPE (2-CPE) was made with 2 mg graphite powder, 2 mg complex 2, and the right amount of paraffin oil in an agate mortar for around half an hour to achieve even mixing. Then, it was added to a 3-mm inner diameter Teflon tube and connected to a copper wire to establish electrical contact. The cyclic voltammograms of the 2-CPE in 0.5 mol·L −1 NaOH solution are shown in Figure S6 (ESI †). It can be seen clearly that in the potential range of +400 to −800, a reversible redox peak is observed for 2-CPE, which could be attributed to the redox of Cu(II)/Cu(I) [CITATION_1] . E 1/2 = (E pa + E pc )/2 was −219.5 mV (50 mV/s) for 2-CPE.",
